column5: 4;21;0.4;1933;**Nombre del conflicto internacional:** El Crack de 1929.  **Razones principales del conflicto:** Las principales causas del Crack de 1929 incluyen: - Especulación financiera excesiva. - Sobreproducción agrícola e industrial. - Desorden monetario internacional. - Desigual distribución de la renta. - Crisis del sistema de crédito y bancario.  **Proceso histórico en el que se desenvuelve:** El conflicto se desarrolla en un contexto de post-Primera Guerra Mundial
column6: donde el mundo estaba en un proceso de reconstrucción y crecimiento económico
column7: especialmente durante los años 1920. Este periodo fue marcado por un auge económico seguido de una profunda crisis que llevó a la Gran Depresión.  **Países involucrados y afectados:** El Crack de 1929 afectó principalmente a Estados Unidos
column9: impactando a países desarrollados y en vías de desarrollo. Europa
column10: ya debilitada por la Primera Guerra Mundial
column11: sufrió gravemente. Países como Alemania
column12: Francia
column13: Reino Unido
column14: y muchos otros en América Latina y Asia también fueron afectados.  **Duración del conflicto:** El Crack de 1929 marcó el inicio de la Gran Depresión
column15: que duró aproximadamente una década
column16: desde 1929 hasta finales de los años 1930.  **Consecuencias y manifestaciones del conflicto:** Las consecuencias incluyeron: - Quiebras masivas de empresas y bancos. - Alto desempleo. - Caída del comercio internacional. - Deflación prolongada. - Crisis social y política que facilitó el auge de regímenes totalitarios en Europa (como el nazismo en Alemania y el fascismo en Italia). - Reestructuración de políticas económicas
column17: incluyendo el New Deal en Estados Unidos.  **Medios de comunicación usados para enterarse de lo sucedido:** Durante esta época
column18: los medios de comunicación predominantes eran la radio
column19: los periódicos y el cine. Estos medios fueron cruciales para informar al público sobre los acontecimientos económicos y sus repercusiones.  ;360;Spanish;Informative;Persuasive;https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-30-jSpWqJDOR1hGP.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-bre-u3sq03ehE6qR.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-DJoDrMbQaYtcuZMb.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-DR0MheN5JGaXOhP1.png||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-f2F7NDe5OQghOsqZ.png||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-LJco6ysNYEbwjm9r.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-q7ePhswf_DHod_3R.png||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-s_3xwOTSjklBQhJO.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-t_qOhoFNV4Kw1MFx.png||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_27_05_01_27-tZuZSjuJSPkOzoOn.png;El Crack de 1929: Un Conflicto Económico que Sacudió al Mundo

column4: 6;471;21;0.4;2798;Nightingale Nursing and rehab Healthy Management: Congestive Heart failure: Management and Prevention Congestive Heart Failure: CHF
column5: Heart Failure: The Heart Muscle has become less able to contract over time or has a mechanical problem that limits its ability to fill with blood and cannot keep up with the bodies demands and blood returns to the heart faster then it can be “pumped out” and it can become Congested or Backed up. This causes the slow down of oxygen rich blood to other vital organs. This may cause the heart to compensate by beating faster
column7: and the lungs may fill with fluid
column8: and make you feel Short of Breath. The Kidneys compensate by holding onto to water and sodium
column9: this may be gradual or sudden. column1: Agro-Fiber Ltd takes pride in its rich heritage of agricultural excellence. With years of experience
column2: we have mastered the art of cultivating and processing sisal fibers. Our commitment to eco-friendly practices
column3: community development
column4: and a diverse range of grades sets us apart in the market.

column1: Our product portfolio boasts a spectrum of sisal fiber grades
column2: each tailored to specific applications and industries. From the coarsest fibers ideal for agricultural twines to the finer
column3: meticulously processed strands suitable for textile and crafts
column4: Agro-Fiber Ltd ensures that every grade meets stringent quality benchmarks. Visit our [Products](http://sisal-processors.com/products) page for detailed insights into the characteristics and applications of each grade.

column1: - *Agricultural Grade:* Robust and durable fibers catering to the needs of the agricultural sector for twine and cordage applications.
- *Textile Grade:* Finer strands crafted with precision for textile manufacturing
column2: providing strength and durability to woven and knitted products.

column1: - *Crafts and Artisanal Grade:* Sisal fibers designed for creative expression
column2: offering versatility and eco-friendly options for artisans and craftspeople.

column1: Agro-Fiber Ltd is not confined by borders; our sisal fibers reach markets worldwide
column2: contributing to sustainable solutions on a global scale. Our extensive export markets include
column3: but are not limited to:

column1: - *North America:* Providing eco-conscious solutions to industries in the United States and Canada.
- *Europe:* Serving the demand for sustainable fibers in various European countries committed to environmental responsibility.
- *Asia:* Meeting the diverse needs of industries across Asia with our high-quality sisal fiber products.
- *Africa:* Collaborating with local industries to promote economic growth and sustainable practices within the continent.
- *Oceania:* Contributing to eco-friendly initiatives in Australia and New Zealand.
Our commitment to quality extends beyond borders. Agro-Fiber Ltd ensures that every shipment maintains the highest standards
column2: complying with international regulations and meeting the specific requirements of each market.

- **1950s:** Expansión global con mejoras en comercio y transporte.
- **1983:** Mayor crecimiento debido a la liberalización del comercio y reducción de costos.
**c) Ventajas y desventajas de las multinacionales:**
| Crean empleos y mejoran ingresos.     | Influyen en gobiernos y exportan ganancias. |
| Transfieren tecnología.               | Explotan recursos y condiciones laborales. |
Multinacionales se ubican en países subdesarrollados por costos bajos y leyes laxas
column3: pero también explotando recursos y causando daños ambientales.

column1: - **Cartel:** Acuerdos entre empresas para evitar competencia.
Las multinacionales deben actuar de manera responsable en los países donde operan
column3: protegiendo el medio ambiente
column4: y asegurando condiciones laborales justas. El informe de Oxfam destaca la falta de compromiso de muchas grandes empresas en estas áreas

column5: 2;21;0.4;2410;"What to Know About the JN.1 Variant of the COVID-19 Virus

column1: A new variant of the virus that causes COVID-19 is rising to prominence in the U.S. as winter illness season approaches its peak: JN.1
JN.1 was first detected in the U.S. in September but spread slowly at first. In recent weeks
column3: it has accounted for a growing percentage of test samples sequenced by labs affiliated with the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)

column1: surpassing 20% during the two-week period ending Dec. 9. By some projections
column2: it will be responsible for at least half of new infections in the U.S. before December ends.

column1: Is JN.1 more infectious or severe than other SARS-CoV-2 variants?
JN.1 is closely related to BA.2.86
column2: a fellow Omicron descendent that first popped up in the U.S. this past summer. The two variants are nearly identical
column3: according to the CDC
column4: except for a single difference in their spike proteins
column5: the part of the virus that allows it to invade human cells.

column1: The fact that JN.1 is responsible for a growing portion of infections suggests it is either more contagious or better at getting past our bodies’ immune defenses than previous iterations of the virus
column2: the CDC says. But right now there is no evidence that it causes more severe disease than other viral strains
column3: even though it may cause a bump in transmission
column4: the CDC says. Primary symptoms are likely to be the same as those from previous variants: a sore or scratchy throat
column5: fatigue
column7: congestion
column9: and fever.

column3: and treatments work against JN.1?

column2: the signs are positive. COVID-19 tests and treatments are expected to be effective against JN.1
column3: the CDC says. And even though the latest COVID-19 booster shot was designed to target the XBB.1.5 variant
column4: preliminary research suggests it also generates antibodies that work against JN.1
column5: albeit fewer of them. (As ever
column6: vaccines will not totally block JN.1 infections
column7: but should reduce the likelihood of death and severe disease.)

column2: WHO’s expert COVID-19 vaccine advisory group recommended sticking with the current XBB.1.5 vaccines
column3: since they seem to provide at least some cross protection.

column1: The best defenses against JN.1—and other variants of SARS-CoV-2—remain getting vaccinated
column3: and limiting exposure to people who may have been infected.";360;English;Detailed;Neutral;https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-5PbXlcBTK7wH-ceh.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-dXV0rVaNF0eOTGLD.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-fI32StoFaua0iAir.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-HUPh9-qvz7Kiw8KE.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-if35CFhFWotBEXKI.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-p7hoiIBkFLFnqXXh.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-pkbjT2QSJlubGZew.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-rIqkcr6caHFXU9KR.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-tbOoj1n2vbk1bw1J.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_39-xyNpqqSS5fkVyaW3.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_40-4KT10tktqusoAZTf.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_40-FBwVQXRmChZw-1F4.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_30_01_11_40-w16No7QWdQqobLkJ.jpeg;Understanding the JN.1 Variant: What You Need to Know

5;6;24;6;1;0;0;1;0;1;646,3;288,5;959;482,7;21;0.4;1934;RadiationTitle: Enhancing Cancer Treatment: The Synergy of Radiation and Hyperthermia
- Radiation therapy is a vital cancer treatment
column2: with nearly 50% of patients undergoing this procedure during their care.

column3: leading to its limited use in the past.

column1: - Technological advancements now allow for targeted radiation delivery
- Stereotactic doses enable higher radiation levels
column3: including damage to blood vessels and low oxygen levels in cells
column4: leading to treatment resistance and tumor recurrence.

column1: - Hyperthermia involves raising the temperature of the body or specific areas to 40-45 degrees Celsius
column2: targeting cancer cells in low oxygen conditions.

column1: - It complements radiation therapy by preventing DNA repair in cancer cells
column2: thus enhancing the effectiveness of radiation treatment.

column1: - Hyperthermia halts DNA repair in cancer cells post-radiation
- Pre-radiation hyperthermia increases oxygen supply to cancer cells
column2: promoting the efficacy of radiation therapy.
treatment conditions such as the time interval between radiation and hyperthermia application need to be defined.

column1: - Determining the optimum hyperthermia temperature is crucial to enhancing treatment outcomes.
- My PhD project focuses on using mouse and cancer models to define the time intervals between radiation and hyperthermia application
- The synergy between radiation and hyperthermia offers promising avenues for improving cancer treatment outcomes
column2: and my research aims to contribute to this advancement.

column2: and shall be regulated by the precepts of the law which establishes them; and as to what has not been foreseen
column3: by the provisions of this Book. (1090)  Legal obligations.  Article 1168 refers to legal obligations or obligations arising from law. They are not presumed because they are considered a burden upon the obligor. They are the exception
column4: not the rule. To be demandable
column5: they must be clearly set forth in the law
column7: the Civil Code or special laws. Thus:  (1) An employer has no obligation to furnish free legal assistance to his employees because no law requires this
column9: an employee may not recover from his employer the amount he may have paid a lawyer hired by him to recover damages caused to said employee by a stranger or strangers while in the pe.formance of his duties. (De la Cruz vs. Northern Theatrical Enterprises
column10: 95 Phil. 739.)  (2) A private school has no legal obligation to provide clothing allowance to its teachers because there is no law which imposes this obligation upon schools. But a person who wins money in gambling has the duty to return his winnings to the loser. This obligation is provided by law. (Art. 2014.)  Under Article 1158
column11: special laws refer to all other laws not contained in the Civil Code. Examples of such laws are Corporation Code
column12: Negotiable Instruments Law
column13: Insurance Code
column14: National Internal Revenue Code
column15: Revised Penal Code
column16: Labor Code

column1: The java.net package of the Java programming language includes various interfaces also that provide an easy-to-use means to access network resources. The interfaces included in the java.net package are as follows:

CookiePolicy – The CookiePolicy interface in the java.net package provides the classes for implementing various networking applications. It decides which cookies should be accepted and which should be rejected. In CookiePolicy
column2: there are three pre-defined policy implementations
column3: namely ACCEPT_ALL
column4: ACCEPT_NONE
column5: and ACCEPT_ORIGINAL_SERVER.

column1: CookieStore – A CookieStore is an interface that describes a storage space for cookies. CookieManager combines the cookies to the CookieStore for each HTTP response and recovers cookies from the CookieStore for each HTTP request.

FileNameMap – The FileNameMap interface is an uncomplicated interface that implements a tool to outline a file name and a MIME type string. FileNameMap charges a filename map ( known as a mimetable) from a data file.
SocketOption – The SocketOption interface helps the users to control the behavior of sockets. Often
column2: it is essential to develop necessary features in Sockets. SocketOptions allows the user to set various standard options.

column1: SocketImplFactory – The SocketImplFactory interface defines a factory for SocketImpl instances. It is used by the socket class to create socket implementations that implement various policies.
ProtocolFamily – This interface represents a family of communication protocols. The ProtocolFamily interface contains a method known as name()
column2: which returns the name of the protocol family.";360;English;Informative;Intellectual;https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05-_JdcZQMwwYVAI3P4.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05--8ztQBTQUAdeyEqU.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05-3BDhfXqhYvn17kdU.webp||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05-61tdh4ltLDAMLUL2.jpeg||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05-C8FVLraunDsW04mD.png||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05-fRpoHX4Q3VVmT83x.png||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05-l44czCKI0Y_NqGWy.png||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05-Mpn47svJYg5CsMiV.png||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05-uP1A0VMo0NFsRanH.png||https://cdn.sendsteps.com/images/slides/2024_31_03_04_05-uUb4JBJsDOufLdMt.jpeg;Exploring the Foundations of Java Networking Interfaces

column1: The core of the material self is the body. Associated with the body are clothes
column3: home and material possessions. Every one pays attention to his/her clothes for his/her clothes reveal who he/she is. Clothes reflect a person's status. Clothes contribute to the formation and maintenance of self-image.

column1: A person's immediate family is a part of his material self. A person identifies with his/her family. If a member of a family does something good
column2: it is the pride and good name of the entire family. On the other hand
column3: if a member of a family does something wrong it is a shame to the whole family. Father and mother
column4: brothers and sisters and if you are married
column5: your wife or husband
column6: are also part of your material self. When someone in the family dies
column7: a part of one's self is gone

column1: A person's home is also part of the material self. This is where a person grows and develops. A person identifies himself/ herself with his/her home.
